SP  - 269
EP  - 281
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/12/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(87)90005-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X87900055
AB  - This paper presents evidence regarding the two quantifiable components of the costs of going public: direct expenses and underpricing. Together, these costs average 21.22% of the realized market value of the securities issued for firm commitment offers and 31.87% for best efforts offers. For a given size offer, the direct expenses are of the same order of magnitude for both contract types, but the underpricing is greater for best efforts offers. An explanation of why some firms choose to use best efforts offers in spite of their apparent higher total costs is given.
ER  - 

